AB  - (Hansen & Galetti 2009), left a legacy of ecosystem dysfunction that threatens the remnant native biota. We and our colleagues in the Mauritian Wildlife Foundation have been studying the effects of taxon substitutes, the Aldabran giant tortoise (Aldabrachelys gigantea )a nd Madagascan radiated tortoise (Astrochelys radiata), on Round Island and Ile aux Aigrettes, two small Mauritian islands. Initial results from this experiment show that these alien tortoises are helping to control weeds that fruit prolifically and outcompete native plants. They also disperse large seeds of native trees, which hitherto rotted under maternal trees, limiting population recruitment and gene flow. Although longer-term monitoring is needed to establish the full impact of the taxon substitutes on these island food webs, preliminary results are encouraging. Should it prove that tortoises have a detrimental impact, they can be removed easily. Many of the arguments against rewilding do not apply to such projects. We believe it is important to undertake carefully controlled, hypothesis-driven experiments and that taxon substitution projects should be evaluated on a case-by-case and locality-by-locality basis, rather than being dismissed outright as having no conservation potential (Caro & Sherman 2009). It is unfortunate that the current focus of the headlinegrabbing and misused term rewilding is on the Pleistocene. Alternative management strategies are needed to preserve biodiversity. Where possible, refaunation with native species should be explored (Oliveira-Santos & Fernandez 2010), although refaunation itself is not riskfree and so should be undertaken under controlled conditions, especially where there has been a significant change in ecosystem structure following extirpation of the species being reintroduced. Altered ecosystem processesmayleadtounexpectedoutcomes.Simultaneously the use of taxon substitutes should be explored when native species are no longer available. Because rewilding has been used frequently and incorrectly as a synonym of reintroduction, future debates should avoid this ambiguous term and ignore Pleistocene extinctions. Terms such as taxon substitution, ecological analogues ,a nd proxy species more accurately describe a process that has the potential to make a significant contribution to minimizing the impacts of ecological perturbations that have occurred with increasing rapidity over the last few hundred years.
